How do states compare in terms of confirmed cases, recovery rate, and mortality rate?¶

In [570]:
statewise = pd.pivot_table(covid_df, values = ['Confirmed', 'Deaths', 'Cured'], 
                           index = 'State/UnionTerritory', aggfunc = 'max')
In [572]:
statewise['Recovery Rate'] = statewise['Cured']*100/statewise['Confirmed']
In [574]:
statewise['Mortality Rate'] = statewise['Deaths']*100/statewise['Confirmed']
In [576]:
statewise = statewise.sort_values(by = 'Confirmed', ascending = False)
In [578]:
statewise.style.background_gradient(cmap = 'cubehelix')

Which states in India have the highest number of active COVID-19 cases?¶

In [580]:
# Top 10 active cases states 

top10_active_cases = covid_df.groupby(by = 'State/UnionTerritory').max()[['Active_Cases', 'Date']].sort_values(by = ['Active_Cases'], ascending = False).reset_index()
In [582]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize = (12,9))
plt.title('Top 10 States with most active cases in India', size = 25)
ax = sns.barplot(data = top10_active_cases.iloc[:10], 
                 y = 'Active_Cases', x = 'State/UnionTerritory', hue = 'State/UnionTerritory',
                 linewidth = 2, edgecolor = 'black', palette = 'Set1')
plt.xlabel('State/UnionTerritory')
plt.ylabel('Total Active Cases')
plt.show()

Which states in India have reported the highest number of COVID-19 deaths?¶

In [586]:
# Top states with highest deaths 

top10_deaths = covid_df.groupby(by = 'State/UnionTerritory').max()[['Deaths', 'Date']].sort_values(by = ['Deaths'], ascending = False).reset_index()

fig1 = plt.figure(figsize = (8,6))
plt.title('Top 10 states with most Deaths', size = 25)
ax = sns.barplot(data = top10_deaths.iloc[:12], y = 'Deaths', x = 'State/UnionTerritory', hue = 'State/UnionTerritory',
                 linewidth = 1.5, edgecolor = 'red', palette = 'Set3')
plt.xlabel('State/UnionTerritory')
plt.ylabel('Total Death Cases')
plt.xticks(rotation = 45)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Which states had the highest number of active COVID-19 cases as of the most recent date available in the dataset?¶

In [588]:
# Ensure Date is datetime type
covid_df['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(covid_df['Date'])

# Filter data for the latest date
latest_date = covid_df['Date'].max()
latest_df = covid_df[covid_df['Date'] == latest_date]

# Sort states by Active Cases (descending) and pick top 5
top_5_states = latest_df.sort_values('Active_Cases', ascending=False).head(5)
print(top_5_states[['State/UnionTerritory', 'Active_Cases']])

Is there a delayed effect of vaccinations on active cases and deaths?¶

In [636]:
# Aggregate daily confirmed cases and deaths
covid_summary = covid_df.groupby('Date')[['Confirmed', 'Cured', 'Deaths']].sum().reset_index()
covid_summary['Active_Cases'] = covid_summary['Confirmed'] - (covid_summary['Cured'] + covid_summary['Deaths'])

# Aggregate daily vaccinations
vaccine_summary = vaccine_df.groupby('Vaccination_Date')[['Total_Doses_Admin']].sum().reset_index()
vaccine_summary.rename(columns={'Vaccination_Date': 'Date'}, inplace=True)
In [638]:
# Merge both datasets
merged_df = pd.merge(covid_summary, vaccine_summary, on='Date', how='inner')

# Compute daily changes
merged_df['Daily Vaccinations'] = merged_df['Total_Doses_Admin'].diff().fillna(0)
merged_df['Daily Change in Deaths'] = merged_df['Deaths'].diff().fillna(0)

# Compute correlation matrix
correlation_deaths = merged_df[['Total_Doses_Admin', 'Daily Vaccinations', 'Deaths', 'Daily Change in Deaths']].corr()

# Plot correlation heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
sns.heatmap(correlation_deaths, annot=True, cmap='coolwarm', fmt=".2f", linewidths=0.5)

plt.title("Correlation Matrix: Vaccinations & Deaths")
plt.show()
In [640]:
merged_df['Vaccinations_Lagged_14'] = merged_df['Daily Vaccinations'].shift(14)
merged_df['Vaccinations_Lagged_28'] = merged_df['Daily Vaccinations'].shift(28)

correlation_lagged_deaths = merged_df[['Vaccinations_Lagged_14', 'Vaccinations_Lagged_28', 'Daily Change in Deaths']].corr()
print(correlation_lagged_deaths)

                        Vaccinations_Lagged_14  Vaccinations_Lagged_28  \

                        Daily Change in Deaths

Vaccinations_Lagged_28                0.735376  
Daily Change in Deaths                1.000000
  • Stronger correlation at a 28-day lag:

A 14-day lag showed a moderate correlation (0.54). A 28-day lag showed a stronger correlation (0.74). This suggests that vaccines needed time to take full effect in reducing mortality.

  • Gradual decrease in deaths with increasing vaccinations:

While deaths initially increased due to the pandemic’s peak, the correlation matrix suggests that higher vaccinations aligned with a reduction in daily death rates over time.

  • Overall trend aligns with expected vaccine impact:

Vaccination rollouts scaled up significantly in response to rising cases and deaths. As vaccine coverage increased, a decline in daily deaths followed. The data suggests a delayed but noticeable impact of vaccinations on reducing mortality.

  • Our analysis demonstrates a strong association between increasing vaccinations and a subsequent decline in deaths. The correlation is more pronounced with a 28-day lag, indicating that vaccines take time to provide protective immunity at a population level. This trend aligns with the expected impact of vaccinations in mitigating severe outcomes and reducing mortality rates over time

statewise_cases = covid_df.groupby('State/UnionTerritory')[['Active_Cases', 'Cured']].sum().reset_index()

# Melt the dataframe for visualization
statewise_cases_melted = statewise_cases.melt(
    id_vars=['State/UnionTerritory'], var_name='Case Type', value_name='Total Cases'
)

# Create a stacked bar chart
fig = px.bar(
    statewise_cases_melted, 
    x='State/UnionTerritory', y='Total Cases', 
    color='Case Type', 
    title='State-wise Proportion of Active vs. Cured Cases',
    labels={'Total Cases': 'Total Count'},
    barmode='relative'  # Makes it a stacked bar chart
)

# Show the plot
fig.show()
  • The state-wise proportion of active vs. cured cases indicates a significant variation in COVID-19 recovery trends across different states.
  • Most states exhibit a higher proportion of cured cases (shown in red) compared to active cases (shown in blue), suggesting effective recovery efforts.
  • However, a few states, such as Maharashtra, Kerala, and Karnataka, show notable active case proportions, indicating ongoing transmission or delayed recovery rates.
  • This visualization highlights the effectiveness of healthcare responses across states and identifies areas where further interventions may be required.

Which states have the highest recovery rates in India?¶

In [654]:
# Compute Recovery Rate
statewise['Recovery_Rate'] = (statewise['Cured'] / statewise['Confirmed']) * 100

# Sort states by highest Recovery Rate
top_states = statewise.sort_values(by='Recovery_Rate', ascending=False).head(15)  # Top 15 states

# Reset index for visualization
top_states = top_states.reset_index()

# Sunburst Chart with increased size
fig = px.sunburst(
    top_states,
    path=['State/UnionTerritory'],  # Hierarchy with just states
    values='Recovery_Rate',
    title="Top States by Recovery Rate",
    color='Recovery_Rate',
    color_continuous_scale='greens',  # Green color scale for better representation
    labels={'Recovery_Rate': 'Recovery Rate (%)'},
    width=900,  # Increased width
    height=600  # Increased height
)

# Show the figure
fig.show()
  • The sunburst chart showcases the states with the highest recovery rates from COVID-19.
  • Delhi, Andaman and Nicobar Islands, and Dadra and Nagar Haveli and Daman and Diu emerge as the top regions with recovery rates close to 95%, indicating a strong healthcare response and effective patient recovery.
  • Other states such as Maharashtra, Uttar Pradesh, Telangana, Bihar, and Ladakh also demonstrate high recovery percentages, reflecting successful containment and treatment measures.
  • The variation in recovery rates across states may be influenced by healthcare infrastructure, testing efficiency, and pandemic management strategies.
